I have had afternoon tea all over the world including at Burj Al Arab in Dubai. 
But having it in Britain 🇬🇧 where it originated has always been on my bucket list! 

There were so many places to choose from and so many variations like Indian themed, French inspired and places like hotels or cozy restaurants but I chose @shangrilalondon so that we could have views from The Shard. 

The restaurant there is beautiful and the Christmas decorations were as well. We lingered for over 2 hours enjoying Champagne 🥂, finger sandwiches, pastries, scones, tea of course 🫖 and live music 🎶! The service was also excellent. 

Do you know the difference between afternoon tea 🫖 and high tea? 

Few things to know about afternoon tea:
🫖 it’s usually served around 4pm on low tables. 
☕️ the food is lighter w pastries, cakes, scones and finger foods and tea 
🍵 It started in Britain 🇬🇧 in the late 19th century as a formal event where Ladies mostly would meet over tea and cakes to gossip-sounds very Bridgerton lol 

Have you had Afternoon Tea? If so where?

Do you have bucket list to-do items for the places you travel to? 
This was my 2nd trip to London in over a decade and I knew there were a few things I wanted to do. I accomplished all 3!! 

1) See a show on the West End. “Get Up Stand Up” tells the story of Bob Marley’s life. It’s a great musical and as a Jamaican I truly enjoyed it 🇯🇲. It’s there until January so try to see it! 

2) Go shopping in Harrods! I wish I had more time here since it was more like a mall than a store. But I did have time to finally buy a Burberry scarf! 

3) Afternoon Tea 🫖 I have done it all over the world 🌍 but it originated in Britain 🇬🇧 so I had to do it here. The scones were AMAZING!! 

What have you done in London? Any of these 3?

On this Saturday morning I’m craving Tahini Simit, Turkish pastries 🥮 & tea ☕️. 
During my visit to Istanbul with @goturkiye I had the chance to do a “Simit” tasting. Simit is compared to a pretzel 🥨 but it’s not salty. Instead of salt it’s embedded usually with sesame seeds although other seeds like flax seeds can be used.  It’s crusty on the outside and soft bread on the inside. There are different types as well. My favorite was the Tahini so definitely try that if you go. 
Simit stands are located all over the city which is really convenient for a quick snack! 
I brought Turkish tea back w me but I should have bought the glasses to get the full effect.

It’s #mardigras2023 ☂️!! There is already so many things to 💟 about New Orleans and last year at #wanderfest held by @sheswanderful I learned of another reason- New Orleans Baby Dolls!

The Baby Dolls date back to around 1910 in Black Storyville-an area of New Orleans referred to as the “red light district”. It was filled with bars, gambling and there was prostitution. There were also brothels and dance halls. 

During Mardi Gras women competed for business. They dressed up in bloomers and bonnets to get attention and even smoked cigars. During these times it was dangerous for women to wear these types of costumes in public. So, they carried bricks and whips as protection 😮

By the 1930s the Baby Dolls became a social group. You had to be chosen to get in. The popularity of the Baby Dolls has gone up and down but after Hurricane Katrina there has been an effort to restore the tradition. 

I’m so glad they did!! What an interesting part of African-American history in New Orleans!! Are you familiar with the #babydollsneworleans ?

****Save & Share for your visit to Napa Valley! 

I love visiting new wineries every time I go to Napa and there are SOOOOOO many to explore. I usually recommend that wine lovers visit places that make the wines they enjoy. Of course Napa is known for Cabernet Sauvignon & Chardonnay but the wineries there make almost all varietals. On this visit I went to 3 and 2 were new to me. 

🍷 @aonair_wine was highly recommended in one of my wine groups! It is located in the hills of St.Helena. Reservations must be made and in peak seasons may be full 4-6 weeks in advance. The property is beautiful with a large patio, fire pit and mountain ⛰️ views of the valley. 

Aonair is a family run business with winemaker Grant Long Jr at the helm. He believes in quantity over quality. Their flagship wines for club members include a Reserve Red Blend and a Reserve Cabernet Sauvignon. I also sampled the Grenache blend, Pinot Noir & the white wine blend.  There is also a Blanc de Noir sparkling!! 

I am not kidding when I say these were some of the best wines I have had in Napa Valley!! They believe in letting the grapes express themselves with low intervention. The best part-low tannins. If you do not like your wines to be too dry-these wines are for you! 🍷🍷🍷

Wines are only available through their club membership or at their tasting room. 

🍷🍷 @josephphelps is also located in St.Helena. The tasting room is stunning including large wine barrels and a patio with views of the valley. Joseph Phelps is one of the pioneers of winemaking in Napa Valley dating back to the 1970s. He focused on making a unique blend each year that represented Joseph Phelps Vineyards. It’s called INSIGNIA. It’s considered Napa 1st Bordeaux style blend. 

Joseph Phelps also makes wines from Sonoma Coast such as Pinot Noir and Chardonnay and sparkling wines and dessert wines. There are so many wines! Allow at least 1 1/2 hours here! 

Have you been to either of these wineries?! 

They were both amazing hosts!

***SAVE FOR YOUR HAWAII TRIP**
Have you wondered which Hawaiian island is right for you? 🌺
Since I have been to Hawaii 3X I get asked this question A LOT. 

It really depends on your interests. The islands all have great things to offer but make sure to do some basic research. 

I chose to go to Kauai on this last trip since I had not been before and I was told it was less “touristy”, quieter and more natural. 

Here are some things you should know about Kauai…

📍Kauai 
1 Fun fact: It is the oldest of the Hawaiian islands. Volcanic activity here ended over 3 million years ago. It is also the northernmost island on the Hawaiian chain 

2 Kauai is known as the “Garden Isle”. Most of the island 🏝️ is a tropical rainforest. IT IS LUSH!! There are stunning valleys, cliffs and waterfalls. Because of this the island has been used as a backdrop for several Hollywood films including Jurassic Park 

3 It is perfect for adventure travelers-hiking, kayaking, snorkeling. There is the 10 mile Waimea Canyon and the Nounou Trails. There is also the Na pali coastline, sea caves…

4 You can take helicopter 🚁 tours that go over dramatic cliffs and waterfalls including Jurassic Park locations 

5 Kauai is less expensive than Maui which is the most expensive island. But it’s more expensive Oahu which remains the cheapest Hawaiian island. 

6 Probably the most important thing-the island is quieter, getting Uber or Lyft is a challenge so it’s best to rent a car, the “town” areas close earlier in the evenings Entertainment at our oceanfront hotel was ZERO, ZIP! This is the island you go to to relax and seek out adventure. 

I hope this helps you decide if you should visit Kauai. Have you been? 

***I had the best Macadamia nut ice cream 🍨 on the island from 2 different places!!!

How often do you see something that takes your breath away?! 😮😮

That’s how I felt when I visited Na Pali coast in Kauai Hawaii! 🌺 

It is located on the North Shore & is 17 miles long with high cliffs & plunging waterfalls, lush green valleys, the most crystal clear water with white sand beaches & alluring sea caves. 

We were lucky because we saw several humpback 🐋 whales!! Including a Mother and baby 🥰it is late in the season for this. We also saw sea turtles. It was so beautiful! 

There are several ways to explore this amazing area. We took a 5 hour sunset 🌅 cruise along the coast. Most tours like this cost around $220-230 and include 1 meal, snacks and drinks/wine or beer. I suggest booking in advance especially on the weekends! 

Other popular tours include helicopter, kayaking and hiking tours. You may recognize some areas used in movies like Manawaiopuna Falls in Jurassic Park. Centuries ago Polynesian explorers settled here and some remnants of these villages still exist. 

If you go to Kauai this is NOT to be missed!! Check out my last post that will help you decide if this island is right for you.

I may be in the French Riviera now (check my stories) but I’m still reliving the amazing culinary adventures we had in Northern Italy 🇮🇹 last month! 

One of the most beautiful stops was @villasandi to do a Prosecco tasting. We spent 2 days in Veneto and made the most of it! This is the area in which Prosecco is from. 

Prosecco is made from the Glera grape 🍇 and made using the Charmat or tank method. This means that secondary fermentation takes place in stainless steels tanks vs in the traditional method used for champagne in which secondary fermentation takes place in the bottle. 

During our tour we were able to visit the caves in which hundreds of bottles of wines are stored and aged. These caves are so old they found World War II artifacts when they were building them out to store the wine!! Hence the picture of the bikes! 

Our tasting was lovely and after the tasting we toured the actual villa, the grounds and then the gift shop. 

If you are looking for the best Prosecco look for the “DOCG” designation. The ones from Veneto made in 
the towns of Conegliano and Valdbiadenne are known to be the best due to steep, rolling hills. These are designate as Prosecco Superior DOCG.

Have you been on a RIVER CRUISE?!! Have you ever considered going on a RIVER CRUISE?!! 

Last month a group from @culinarytravels_thesophislife set sail on our 1st River Cruise with @amawaterways because @theopolisvineyards owner Theodora Lee was the wine host 🍷🍷 

Our ship was the Amacello and our cruise was the “Essence of Burgundy of Provence”. It was a wine themed cruise and it was lovely. 

But before going on a river cruise I did some research and wrote a blog post on thesophisticatedlife.com on the differences between river vs ocean cruises-you should check it out! 

Now that I have been on one, I can say the 3 most important things to be aware of are:

1) the size of the ships-much smaller! Our ship had only 95 passengers, 3 floors with an outdoor area on top (but it was cold), 1 main dining room, 1 main lounge. There was a small gym & spa. But the rooms were the same size as a regular cruise ship. We had a “French” balcony room which meant you could open the sliding doors but there was no place to sit. 

2) Dining. As mentioned above there was 1 main dining room. The dining times are firmly set for 3 meals a day. If you miss these times, you will have to wait until the next meal time. There is no 24 hour in room dining. BUT there is unlimited wine & beer is served with lunch & dinner! There is also cocktail hour daily! We also enjoyed a multi course chef’s table. The food on this ship was the best I can remember having! 

3) Excursions/Tours are included! This is huge! On ocean cruises these are expensive and they add up. But on this river cruise we were able to pick from walking tours, food tours, biking, hiking, morning tours, afternoon tours…

**this was our experience on this river cruise. Others may differ.

Influencers be like…..lol But seriously-our tasting experiences in Northern Italy 🇮🇹 were next level @culinarytravels_thesophislife 

Here are just 3 of our many tasting! 

1) Wine Tasting in Veneto 🍷🍷 I studied this area while taking @wsetglobal Level 2  so I was excited to be here!! 
Valpolicella has a unique wine making technique which is called “appassimento”. The grapes 🍇 are dried after harvest-here on racks-before being fermented which leads to a higher concentration of sugar which later means more alcohol. There is also more tannins in this wine which makes it great for aging. A blend of red grapes are used. You may be familiar with Corvina. Amarone della Valpolicella is the famous dry wine from this area. Recioto is the sweet variety. Have you had either one?? 

2) Street food tasting in Bologna. Bologna was one of my favorite cities on this trip! It was colorful and the streets were vibrant. Live music, shops, an outdoor market. Delicious gelato 🍨! We took a cooking class and I had the best lasagna of my life made with spinach pasta and Ragu Bolognese 😋😋
We also had the opportunity to try a common street food-Mortadella sandwiches. Mortadella is what American baloney is derived from. These sandwiches had different types of Mortadella with cheese and one even had Ragu Bolognese. They were yummy and convenient to eat on the go! 

3) Balsamic Vinegar tasting—did you know balsamic vinegar is aged in barrels similar to wine? We traveled to Modena outside of Bologna to a family owned estate to learn about this process and try 12 and 25 year old vinaigrette! The barrels are stored in the attic! They treated us to brunch made by their Mother and it was amazing as was the 25yo aged Balsamic! When you are buying Balsamic vinegar look at where it was produced and the age!! 

What do you think of these tastings? I aim for unique, interesting and immersive experiences like these on all of my @culinarytravels_thesophislife small group trips. If you love food, wine & culture join us!
